Recommendation:
We recommended to management to adopt the following measures:
In accordance with Item 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006, follow the procedures therein and prepare the accounting entries, with working papers and other relevant documents such as the List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the said COA Circular), copies of the demand letters, to recognize in the books of accounts the loss of PPE and to set up the corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers/personnel for the non-existing/missing PPEs that could not be produced upon demand as well as those with pending Requests for Relief;
Expedite the preparation and submission to the Audit Team of the reports related to “One-time Cleansing” activities specifically for those items subject to COA’s Authority to Derecognize non-existing/missing PPEs;
Ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the MACCO and GSO’s records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the GSO and the PPELCs maintained by the MACCO are reconciled;
Henceforth, consistently ensure that accountable personnel are issued with the corresponding Property Acknowledge Receipts and that a copy of the same is duly filed in the possession of the concerned office in order to easily trace Property, Plant and Equipment; and
The Agency shall endeavor to always adhere with the procedures in relation to Loss of Property as the procedures under COA Circular No. 2020-006 may be availed only once and that any loss of PPE shall be thereafter subject to the usual rules on Loss of Property wherein those who cannot file Requests for Relief of Accountability will eventually be held liable for lost items.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
Observation (a)
The Municipal Accounting Office personnel in-charge of recording deductions and processing remittances in coordination with the HRMO, shall endeavor to prepare a reconciliation schedule with supporting documents for the variances noted under Table 5.1 of this report in order to have a basis for an updated and reconciled balance.
Should adjusting entries be necessary in view of the reconciliation schedule prepared, the same shall be drawn with sufficient supporting documents. A copy of the same shall be subsequently submitted to the Office of the Auditor for reference;
Henceforth, the concerned office shall endeavor to correctly record the deductions and remittances in the books of accounts to the end that the total amount recognized as Due to GSIS and Due to HDMF shall be the same amount recorded as remittance. Should there arise circumstances that would render the recording of deductions and remittances with variances, a reconciliation schedule shall be prepared showing the source and breakdown of the said variances;
The concerned personnel in charge of the DCPC and MEEO books shall see to it that the amounts under Due to GSIS and Due to Pag-IBIG are to be remitted on a monthly basis and prior to the scheduled remittance by the General Fund of GSIS and HDMF contributions and loans in order to avoid the utilization of cash under the General Fund to pay for GSIS and HDMF remittances covering DCPC and MEEO contributions with no cash transferred yet;
Observation (b)
For refunds of alleged GSIS and HDMF over-deductions without supporting documents enumerated in APPENDIX K of this report, the concerned office is to submit the following:
a) Copy of the payroll/s showing the amount and details of the over-deducted amount; and
b) Remittance List stamped ‘Received’ by the HDMF showing that the amount deducted was duly remitted.
Henceforth, ensure that GSIS and HDMF premium and loan payment refunds are supported with certified copies of payroll reflecting the amounts withheld and bill statements of the concerned employees. Non-compliance with this may warrant audit suspension or disallowance, as the case may be;
The office in-charge is to consider maintaining its own monitoring of loan balances of employees and check the same during computation of salaries/wages to avoid under/over-deductions;
Observation (c)
Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries supported with working papers for the transactions in the prior years that caused the negative beginning balance and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor. If the said negative balance cannot still be adjusted at the end of the ensuing calendar year, the same is to be disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements;
Discuss with the system technicians any inconsistency observed in the system generated reports to address immediately erroneous balances, if any.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
Consistently enforce the provisions of Municipal Ordinance No. 2019-026 or the Don Carlos Public Eternal Garden Ordinance - specifically, the payment schemes listed in Section 12 in order to maximize the revenue generating mechanisms of the Agency which could lead to increased funds for public use;
Instruct the concerned office to review the list of occupied and fully paid Crypts, Lawn Lots and Family Estates requiring Burial Contracts and/or Certificates of Ownership and if none has been issued to the owners yet, initiate the drafting and preparation of the same as these documents are vital protection against disputes and enables smooth property transactions by clearly establishing ownership rights and details;
Pending the turnover of the cemetery supervision and management to the proper office which is the MEEMDO, the offices currently involved in the cemetery operations shall initiate the creation and/or maintenance of a systematic and orderly filing system of all deceased persons interred in the cemetery which shows as well all available and sold cemetery products/services to the end that when inquiries are made by stakeholders and other concerned agencies, there is a definitive office to whom they are to be directed to and not merely being passed back and forth in various offices; and
Constantly coordinate with the concerned office for the hastened facilitation of the proposed changes to Municipal Ordinance No. 2019-026. Pending the turn-over of the cemetery supervision and management to the proper office, the current personnel involved in the cemetery operations shall adopt mechanisms in order to avoid operational issues such as those mentioned in this memorandum.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

With regard to completed projects that still remain in the CIP under the Trust Fund, consistently follow-up the preparation and submission of the documents required from various offices/unites (e.g. Inspection Report from the Province of Bukidnon, Report of Supplies and Materials Issued from the Municipal Treasurer’s Office) in order for the implementing agency to fully liquidate the said projects; 

For the completed projects implemented and funded by the LGU but intended for various barangays, the concerned offices shall hasten the determination of the booking of the corresponding asset (e.g. whether to donate the same to the barangay or to retain them in the agency books) in order for the said projects to be deducted from the CIP account, in any case;

With regard to the labor component of completed projects which were not taken up in the CIP account, the following shall be the suggested courses of action:

a. If feasible, the MEO/MPDO/Project Supervisor shall prepare the list of workers assigned to the subject projects and verify with the HRMO whether the said workers are indeed registered in the HRMO’s Facial Scanning System as Job Order personnel whose wages are charged under MOOE. If the same can be established, the concerned office(s) are to conduct the proper procedures to revert the appropriated and/or obligated Labor Component of the projects in view of the LGU’s set up wherein Job Order workers whose wages are charged under MOOE are being utilized in projects implemented by Administration;

3) In relation to recommendation No. 2, henceforth, the Municipal Engineer’s Office, Municipal Planning and Development Office, the Human Resource Management Office, the Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Budget Office shall closely coordinate with each other to the end that proper protocols and procedures are to be established to ensure the following:

a. That the preparation of the Labor Component in the Program of Works for projects implemented by administration which utilize Job Order workers as the labor force in view of the set up adopted by the LGU, shall take into consideration the daily rate of the Job Order workers which are to be assigned to specific projects to the end that the budget for labor in the POW shall not be exceeded by the actual labor cost based on the daily rate and actual duty days of the JO workers;

b. That during the duration of a specific project implemented by Administration, the Job Order workers assigned to it shall fill up a time card/attendance sheet/log book or similar document in order for the Project Supervisor to trace whether the Job Order workers were actually on the project site on a specific day. This shall be in addition to the regular Face Scanning procedures of the HRMO. These document which is to be signed by the Project Supervisor shall then be a supporting document to the payroll of the JO workers;

c. That the implementing unit shall prepare a Statement of Work Accomplished every payroll period which is to be attached together with the workers’ time card/attendance sheet/log book or similar document as mentioned in the preceding paragraph;

d. That the HRMO shall prepare the payroll indicating the specific project where the JO Workers are assigned to in a specific period which shall be based on documents provided by the implementing unit. This shall enable the accounting office to easily determine the booking of the labor component of the project under the CIP account;

e. That during the duration of a specific project implemented by Administration, the Job Order workers assigned to it are not be pulled to do other tasks until the 100% completion of the assigned project. This is to ensure that the project will be completed within the number of days provided for in the POW and moreover, this is to aid the concerned offices in the monitoring of the labor component of the specific project;

f. The timely submission of documents to the person in charge of the preparation of Quarterly Report of PPAs to enable complete data as to Physical and Financial accomplishments and start and completion dates of projects supervised by offices other than the MEO;

With regard to the inclusion of unbilled projects in the CIP and Accounts Payable accounts, the MBO, BAC and MEO shall ensure that reports and documents related to projects and their status are reviewed and verified prior to submitting the same to the Accounting Office in order to avoid erroneous Journal Entries which could affect the fair presentation of the Financial Statements.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Require the person responsible for the preparation of BRS to ensure that this report is 
submitted to the Office of the Auditor within the reglementary period; 

Submit the lacking BRS for CY 2023 as listed in ANNEX A of this report. Kindly note that that this AOM and its related recommendation likewise serves as a demand 
letter to submit the aforementioned BRS;

Draw adjusting Journal Entries for the reconciling items, especially those which are long standing, which are to be supported with working papers which shall then be submitted to the Office of the Auditor for verification;

Constantly ensure that reconciling items are adjusted on a monthly basis to avoid long standing items in the BRS which could lead to difficulty in tracing the same.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Require the person responsible for the preparation of Real Property tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year to prepare the same in time for the recording of the RPT and SET Receivable at the beginning of each year;

Furnish the MACCO a copy of the said report mentioned in the preceding recommendation on a timely basis so that the said office can setup the appropriate amounts to be recorded as RPT & SET Receivable at the beginning of the year;Expedite the creation Inventory Committee who shall then be the spearhead in conducting physical count of inventories and other properties owned by the LGU;

Consistently ensure that the amounts set up for RPT & SET Receivable at the beginning of each year are of equal amounts;

If still practicable, draw a Journal Entry Voucher to correct the advance payment for CY 2024 recognized as income in CY 2023 and submit the same with supporting working papers to the Office of the Auditor for verification; and

Consistently follow the pro-forma accounting entries for RPT collections and remittance provided in Annex A of the related AOM issued. Apply the same for SET but observe the 50:50 sharing between the Municipality and the Province.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Submit to this office the justification and legal basis for the acquisition of the above-mentioned textile materials and polo shirts without going through the allowed Modes of Procurement;

Submit to this office the supporting documents such as the Official Receipt, Charge Invoice and similar documents showing the actual cost paid by the concerned office to the supplier of the textile materials.

The non-submission of the documents required in recommendation Nos. 1 and 2 or the incompleteness and/or insufficiency of the submitted documents may subject the transaction to Suspension or Disallowance, if warranted;

Consistently ensure that all funds of the government are expended or utilized in accordance with law and regulations for the purpose of ensuring transparency, efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the operations of the government; and

Consistently ensure that the acquisition of goods and/or services shall be made through any of the Modes of Procurement allowed by RA No. 9184 and its Implementing Rules and Regulations.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures: 

Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the “Unidentified Subsidiary   Accounts” in the subsidiary ledgers of the all mentioned real accounts to establish fair presentation, reliability and accuracy of the CY 2022 Statement of Financial Position accounts; 

Expedite the creation of Inventory Committee and commence the procedures laid out in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in order to analyze and review the existence, validity and accuracy of PPE items including those that comprised the bulk of unreconciled balances and effect necessary adjusting entries after reconciliation following the procedures provided for in the aforementioned circular; 

With regard to the Accounts Payable specifically, prepare an aging of accounts payable and/or evaluate the existing aging schedule and determine whether the long-standing payables are based on a valid claim and exert diligent effort to locate its supporting documents and if found to be no longer payable or without valid and actual claims, draw the proper adjusting journal entries;

Review projects/programs funded by National Government Agencies and verify whether appropriate entries were made upon their liquidation and if determined to have not been made, make the necessary journal entries supported by the appropriate documents for the unrecorded liquidation or unliquidated balances.

